Swordsmen are melee fighters trained in individual blade mastery through the dueling court tradition.
The tradition was born in city-state dueling courts where legal disputes were settled at blade-point with formal rules and documentation.
The Cutting Books are the codified manuals of blade theory covering timing, measure, decision-making, and initiative management.
Later Cutting Books address psychological territory: reading opponent intention and mental states under pressure.
Combat role is high-skill single-combatant melee with escalating momentum and precise force application.
Core doctrine: at the highest levels of blade skill, individual decision-making speed exceeds what formation discipline can constrain.
Schools competed through graduates' dueling performance, driving continuous refinement of technique.
Swordsmen contrast with Knights, who emphasize formation coordination over individual excellence.
The Crusader class synthesizes Swordsman escalating momentum with Knight body-strike mechanics.
